##From the diary of a patient who was cured of the disease: through the ordeal of life and death, I've summarized these six pieces of advice | deep web

By Mu Wen, a college teacher in Wuhan
To protect the author's privacy, Muwen goes by a pseudonym
Production | Deep Net tencent Xiaoman studio

Welcome to download tencent news APP for more quality information

Editor's Note: through the perspective of ordinary people in Hubei cities and anti-epidemic action, recorded this unforgettable history. Is the fifth diary series for the fight against the epidemic, from a university teacher in Wuhan infected with the virus after the first-hand experience of cure, oral content edited by the Deep Web.

Looking back on my entire experience, the first thing I would like to express is my gratitude. I would like to express my gratitude to all the family members, colleagues, classmates, friends and medical staff who have helped and cared for me. They are in my most difficult time, always accompany at my side, for me to solve the problem.

It is because of the power of this emotion that I have the motivation to persevere, to fight the disease.

From coughing to alertness

Before I developed the suspected symptoms, I had two days of travel history between different districts in Wuhan. On January 18, I took my daughter, who is less than 3 years old, for a stroll in downtown Wuhan, the Pedestrian Street of Jianghan road, the entrance of Si men, the second-hand car market in Zhuye Mountain, Hankou (to help my sister buy a car) . Public Transport has taken buses, taxis, ferries, the subway. In Wuhan before the 20th, people were busy buying new year goods. The whole city was ordinary and festive. With the exception of a few, most people are almost unguarded against the virus.

On the evening of the 18th, with my daughter, my sister and my nephew, I drove my sister's new car back to my hometown in the suburbs. On the morning of the 19th, I returned with my daughter from our suburban home to our home in downtown Wuchang, on the afternoon of the 19th, my daughter and my family went to Walmart in Pingmao, Wuchang, to purchase a New Year's Eve -- a large supermarket on the ground floor. What struck me most was how few people wore masks in this crowded, airless supermarket. On the afternoon of the 20th, my family drove back to our hometown in the suburbs.

The author's daughter, January 18, Wuhan

That night I began to have a dry cough. What I remember clearly was that I had been following the progress of the epidemic with my mobile phone, and discussing the details of the epidemic with various friends around me. The basic manifestation of this dry cough was: no phlegm, but there was a clear feeling of foreign body in my throat, you always want to clear the throat of these foreign bodies out, but how to clear away.
Because of the symptoms, and because I had spent so much time focusing on the disease, I became emotionally alert that night, Random Thoughts. One Minute you're suggesting you don't have the new coronavirus, the next you're worried you might have it. I couldn't sleep all night.

The next day, January 21, I began to drink a lot of water, holding a glass of water and keep drinking. But the phenomenon of dry cough has no substantial improvement, to the evening, cough action gradually frequent. In order not to affect the rest of the family, I try to keep my voice down and cover my conscious mouth.

At the same time, in order to give myself confidence and comfort, I began to analyze my usual physical condition and the itinerary of these days, and then suggested to myself: I should not be so unlucky to catch it, you shouldn't be afraid if you get it. Another nearly sleepless night.

On January 22, I began to feel tightness in my chest, as well as nausea from eating. I kept my family at arm's length, but I still didn't share my concerns or tell them about my symptoms. The atmosphere in their home was still like a happy Spring Festival -- I didn't want to disturb them.

But I knew better than anyone about my own health, and I began to feel worse. In addition to the constant attention to Wechat News, constantly discuss with people about the epidemic of various issues. Especially to see a variety of spread from the medical staff, close friends and relatives of the so-called "first-line scene. ".

I spent most of the day looking over my shoulder. When I go to bed at night, I struggle with myself and play out the details of the epidemic in my mind. Once again, I spent the night in a state of shock.

January 23rd, early morning. I spoke openly with my family about my physical symptoms and my concerns. My family blamed me for making a big deal out of it, thinking, how could this happen to our family! But I tried to tell them that I had to go to the hospital for my family's health and my own responsibility.

So that morning I drove to the People's Hospital in the suburbs. After asking at the guide station, I was told to go to the respiratory department. After a few simple procedures, I went to the smoking department of the hospital. According to the number of the call machine, there are about 200 people in the morning in the respiratory department. The nurse on duty told me to go in the afternoon. I'M NOT GONNA make it in the morning. So I left the hospital, went to the nearby supermarket and bought some supplies again; then I drove home. I was back at the hospital at 1:30 p.m. Sharp, and there was still a long line of smokers. When the hospital opened at 2:00, I headed to Florida, where there were 64 people in front of me. I spent the afternoon waiting, anxious, in the hospital. By the time I finished my doctor's appointment and C.T. , it was nearly 6 p.m.

The doctor's initial diagnosis: Low fever, ruled out influenza, normal lungs, bronchial inflammation. Knowing that there was no infection in his lungs made him feel more relaxed. When I got home, I had an early dinner and went to bed early. Still, the quality of sleep was poor that day.

January 24th, New Year's Eve. I woke up this morning feeling good. Work hard with your family and prepare a family reunion dinner together. Have a family reunion dinner and play with your children. Everything seems to be going back to normal.

Around 3:00 in the afternoon, people started feeling sick again. The main symptom is fatigue, wanting to lie down, and then feeling depressed again, as if the feeling of being depressed is heavier than before. By the end of the day, the pain in my chest had started, I was sweating and I had a low fever (37.5) .

Then I realized again that things could be really bad, and I decided to talk to my family about the situation and my health, and I told them: I have to stay away from everyone and go home to Wuchang alone.

At this point, the family may also realize the seriousness of the problem, they are reluctant but still support my decision. So I rode fast, through the various paths, a person drove back to the Wuchang home. I had a lot of chest pain and a lot of choking while driving. It was about ten o'clock when I got home. I instantly connected with people I could reach out to -- a community, a hospital, a college. I asked if I could find a hospital for detailed admission as soon as possible. In spite of all the eagerness to communicate and coordinate,. But the hospital beds in Wuhan were tight at that time. After carefully consulting the opinions of the doctors in the hospital and so on, I decided to quarantine at home.

Isolation and hospitalization

January 25, the first day of the Lunar New Year. When I was alone in my home in Wuchang, I felt lost and helpless in two ways: physical symptoms persisted and tended to get worse; and in the second place, I couldn't tell if I was infected or not, how far along is the infection, and what should I do?

Fortunately, I got a lot of advice and information from my friends through my wechat friend circle. I read them one by one and began to practice them in a targeted way. During this time I began to keep track of my physical state. On this day, almost all of the previous symptoms were present, and there was one more symptom -- a feeling of fullness, a feeling of discomfort. The feeling of wanting to shit and not being able to shit.

By the end of the day, the body temperature starts to rise to 39 degrees. It's after 10:00, starts sweating, breathes heavily -- a heady urge to inhale. I started to panic. Lying in bed, I kept repeating the same thought: Can I be cured? Will I infect the whole family? What am I GONNA do?

With the help of my colleagues and leaders, I was finally taken by ambulance to a hospital in Wuchang District, which had just been requisitioned for the treatment of fever patients, i was admitted to the isolation ward of the hospital.

After I was admitted to the isolation ward, the doctors and nurses came and gave me various basic physical examinations and consultations. Then they drew my blood, gave me injections, and gave me two boxes of antiviral drugs —— as I remember it, Chano and Oseltamivir.

There are doctors and nurses, in the hospital this night is the most reassuring, after taking medicine about 12 o'clock, I put down the phone, began to sleep. I had a good night's sleep.

26 January. I woke up this morning feeling refreshed. And then picked up the phone and kept around the friends and relatives to check in. I could hardly stop playing with my phone, and I forgot to eat and take my medicine. It wasn't until after two in the afternoon, when I felt a little hungry and my body started to feel sick again, that I realized I should stop and have a rest. So I lay in bed and rested.

Around four o'clock, the pain in my chest got to the point where it had worsened since the onset of symptoms, and I could feel a sharp contraction of my entire abdomen, followed only by breathing in and barely breathing out. At some point, the inhalation almost stops. I can feel my whole body shutting down. But I was wide awake, trying to keep my eyes open and tell myself I couldn't sleep, couldn't close them. Then my hand gripped the sheet, sweating profusely.

After about a minute or so, I felt myself coming through, and the breathing began to recover. And so many wonderful things happened in my body, as if I could feel that there was a force at work, a force that was trying to beat the virus.

This continued into the night, and I didn't fall asleep the whole night. I feel my body changing because I don't know what's going on in my body right now, whether I'm safe, whether I'm in danger if I close my eyes and sleep, etc. .

27 January. Keep Your Eyes Open till dawn. I felt extremely tired and hungry. I had my family whip up some goodies for me. I have been eating and sweating all day. I'm still very worried because I'm still not quite sure where I stand physically.

Around 11 am, I had another fever, drenched in sweat, and my mind seemed to be caught in a fog -- as if I was dreaming, Dreaming Strange Dreams. Until about 12:00, when I woke up. When I woke up, I felt as if I was going back to being hungry.

And then quickly bring the family over the food, can eat all the food, food is particularly bloated. After eating, and the people around me to declare peace.

Because during my high fever, I made a lot of unintelligible remarks in the circle of friends; all the friends who cared about me in the circle of friends, especially those close to me, were frightened. After telling everyone I was all right, I lay down again to rest.

By the end of the day, I was eating, trying to make it to the bathroom, and then I went back to bed. In the meantime, I told the doctor I wanted a CT scan of my lungs. Since I was admitted on the 25th, doctors and nurses have given me all kinds of routine tests, taking my temperature, taking my blood pressure, taking Oxygenation, etc. . The hospital has just been changed to a regular admission hospital, and the hospital is undergoing department and personnel adjustments, so the whole hospital was very busy; halfway through I reported my discomfort to the doctor, who kept telling me that I was fine.

Around 8:00 p.m. , I went in for a checkup. The doctor took the film and said it was not a big problem -- just an increase in the texture of the lungs. He could be released soon and go home.

Reflection and conclusion

Looking back over my entire experience, the first thing I want to express is my gratitude. It is because of the emotional strength of my family, colleagues and friends that I have the motivation to persevere and to keep fighting my illness.

The second piece of reflection I'd like to share with my friends is this: whether or not you are sure you have the virus, you must first be at peace with yourself; if the illness is a four, the illness is a six. Especially for those of us in our 30s and 40s, we are likely to bear a heavy psychological burden in the face of this unknown disease because we have young and old. Once we carry a heavy psychological burden, our immune system may be affected, so our body will be trapped in a vicious cycle, also is not conducive to our fight against the virus.

The third point is a more concrete reflection: don't focus too much on the epidemic and the information related to the virus, do Not make any mild physical discomfort as a psychological cue -- compare the symptoms to those caused by the virus. Don't spend too much time on your phone. To adjust the pace of life, especially to ensure a good sleep.

Then there is the fourth point: If your symptoms are increasing and getting worse, you should consider going to the hospital for a check up as soon as possible, and if conditions permit, you should get a diagnosis. Of course, the reality of the situation in Wuhan is that medical resources are stretched, medical staff are overworked, and you have to balance your physical condition with the reality of the situation. As soon as your body sends out certain distinct signals -- like fever, high fever, shortness of breath, etc. . Then you should find a way to get to a doctor in time.

At the same time, it's important to note that you should be completely separated from your family.

Fifth Point: The virus infection, from the current official data, objectively speaking, it is mainly concentrated in the elderly and people with major underlying diseases or immune system deficiencies of these three groups, they are prone to severe or critical illness and even death. For people who do not belong to these groups, the symptoms of infection will be relatively mild.

As long as you observe good hygiene and strengthen the body's immune system, you can heal yourself. My above summary is of course only "general situation" , and each person's physical condition or infection situation is very different, so we must analyze the specific problem.

Sixth: Whether or not to fight this virus, we ordinary people in later life should pay attention to personal hygiene and public health: Wash hands frequently, when necessary to wear masks, frequent disinfection ventilation; do not eat wild animals and so on. Let's hope this outbreak is a "hygienic" enlightenment for the rest of us.

Finally: My beloved city and hometown have been in some kind of "abnormal" state for a long time, and the people here have gone through or are going through perhaps the most trying and extraordinary period of their lives. Not only are they under extreme physical stress, but they are also under tremendous psychological stress. All of this, too suddenly, too heavily. I hope you will all try to be as tolerant and rational as possible. Please support them. Please love them.

If only we could beat the epidemic, if only we could make peace with the world!

Isolation and hospitalization

January 25, the first day of the Lunar New Year. When I was alone in my home in Wuchang, I felt lost and helpless in two ways: physical symptoms persisted and tended to get worse; and in the second place, I couldn't tell if I was infected or not, how far along is the infection, and what should I do?

Fortunately, I got a lot of advice and information from my friends through my wechat friend circle. I read them one by one and began to practice them in a targeted way. During this time I began to keep track of my physical state. On this day, almost all of the previous symptoms were present, and there was one more symptom -- a feeling of fullness, a feeling of discomfort. The feeling of wanting to shit and not being able to shit.

By the end of the day, the body temperature starts to rise to 39 degrees. It's after 10:00, starts sweating, breathes heavily -- a heady urge to inhale. I started to panic. Lying in bed, I kept repeating the same thought: Can I be cured? Will I infect the whole family? What am I GONNA do?

With the help of my colleagues and leaders, I was finally taken by ambulance to a hospital in Wuchang District, which had just been requisitioned for the treatment of fever patients, i was admitted to the isolation ward of the hospital.

After I was admitted to the isolation ward, the doctors and nurses came and gave me various basic physical examinations and consultations. Then they drew my blood, gave me injections, and gave me two boxes of antiviral drugs —— as I remember it, Chano and Oseltamivir.

There are doctors and nurses, in the hospital this night is the most reassuring, after taking medicine about 12 o'clock, I put down the phone, began to sleep. I had a good night's sleep.

26 January. I woke up this morning feeling refreshed. And then picked up the phone and kept around the friends and relatives to check in. I could hardly stop playing with my phone, and I forgot to eat and take my medicine. It wasn't until after two in the afternoon, when I felt a little hungry and my body started to feel sick again, that I realized I should stop and have a rest. So I lay in bed and rested.

Around four o'clock, the pain in my chest got to the point where it had worsened since the onset of symptoms, and I could feel a sharp contraction of my entire abdomen, followed only by breathing in and barely breathing out. At some point, the inhalation almost stops. I can feel my whole body shutting down. But I was wide awake, trying to keep my eyes open and tell myself I couldn't sleep, couldn't close them. Then my hand gripped the sheet, sweating profusely.

After about a minute or so, I felt myself coming through, and the breathing began to recover. And so many wonderful things happened in my body, as if I could feel that there was a force at work, a force that was trying to beat the virus.

This continued into the night, and I didn't fall asleep the whole night. I feel my body changing because I don't know what's going on in my body right now, whether I'm safe, whether I'm in danger if I close my eyes and sleep, etc. .

27 January. Keep Your Eyes Open till dawn. I felt extremely tired and hungry. I had my family whip up some goodies for me. I have been eating and sweating all day. I'm still very worried because I'm still not quite sure where I stand physically.

Around 11 am, I had another fever, drenched in sweat, and my mind seemed to be caught in a fog -- as if I was dreaming, Dreaming Strange Dreams. Until about 12:00, when I woke up. When I woke up, I felt as if I was going back to being hungry.

And then quickly bring the family over the food, can eat all the food, food is particularly bloated. After eating, and the people around me to declare peace.

Because during my high fever, I made a lot of unintelligible remarks in the circle of friends; all the friends who cared about me in the circle of friends, especially those close to me, were frightened. After telling everyone I was all right, I lay down again to rest.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By the end of the day, I was eating, trying to make it to the bathroom, and then I went back to bed. In the meantime, I told the doctor I wanted a CT scan of my lungs. Since I was admitted on the 25th, doctors and nurses have given me all kinds of routine tests, taking my temperature, taking my blood pressure, taking Oxygenation, etc. . The hospital has just been changed to a regular admission hospital, and the hospital is undergoing department and personnel adjustments, so the whole hospital was very busy; halfway through I reported my discomfort to the doctor, who kept telling me that I was fine.

Around 8:00 p.m. , I went in for a checkup. The doctor took the film and said it was not a big problem -- just an increase in the texture of the lungs. He could be released soon and go home.

Reflection and conclusion

Looking back over my entire experience, the first thing I want to express is my gratitude. It is because of the emotional strength of my family, colleagues and friends that I have the motivation to persevere and to keep fighting my illness.

The second piece of reflection I'd like to share with my friends is this: whether or not you are sure you have the virus, you must first be at peace with yourself; if the illness is a four, the illness is a six. Especially for those of us in our 30s and 40s, we are likely to bear a heavy psychological burden in the face of this unknown disease because we have young and old. Once we carry a heavy psychological burden, our immune system may be affected, so our body will be trapped in a vicious cycle, also is not conducive to our fight against the virus.

The third point is a more concrete reflection: don't focus too much on the epidemic and the information related to the virus, do Not make any mild physical discomfort as a psychological cue -- compare the symptoms to those caused by the virus. Don't spend too much time on your phone. To adjust the pace of life, especially to ensure a good sleep.

Then there is the fourth point: If your symptoms are increasing and getting worse, you should consider going to the hospital for a check up as soon as possible, and if conditions permit, you should get a diagnosis. Of course, the reality of the situation in Wuhan is that medical resources are stretched, medical staff are overworked, and you have to balance your physical condition with the reality of the situation. As soon as your body sends out certain distinct signals -- like fever, high fever, shortness of breath, etc. . Then you should find a way to get to a doctor in time.

At the same time, it's important to note that you should be completely separated from your family.

Fifth Point: The virus infection, from the current official data, objectively speaking, it is mainly concentrated in the elderly and people with major underlying diseases or immune system deficiencies of these three groups, they are prone to severe or critical illness and even death. For people who do not belong to these groups, the symptoms of infection will be relatively mild.

As long as you observe good hygiene and strengthen the body's immune system, you can heal yourself. My above summary is of course only "general situation" , and each person's physical condition or infection situation is very different, so we must analyze the specific problem.

Sixth: Whether or not to fight this virus, we ordinary people in later life should pay attention to personal hygiene and public health: Wash hands frequently, when necessary to wear masks, frequent disinfection ventilation; do not eat wild animals and so on. Let's hope this outbreak is a "hygienic" enlightenment for the rest of us.

Finally: My beloved city and hometown have been in some kind of "abnormal" state for a long time, and the people here have gone through or are going through perhaps the most trying and extraordinary period of their lives. Not only are they under extreme physical stress, but they are also under tremendous psychological stress. All of this, too suddenly, too heavily. I hope you will all try to be as tolerant and rational as possible. Please support them. Please love them.

If only we could beat the epidemic, if only we could make peace with the world!
